======================================================================
PART 1: CARTAN DETERMINANTS — THE KEYS FOR EACH LIE ALGEBRA
======================================================================

For type A_n: det = n+1
  A₁: det=2, A₂: det=3, A₃: det=4, ..., A₈: det=9
  THESE ARE OUR KEYS: 2 and 3 from A₁ and A₂

Cartan determinants of all simple Lie algebras:

Classical series:
  A_1: det = 2
  A_2: det = 3
  A_3: det = 4
  A_4: det = 5
  A_5: det = 6
  A_6: det = 7
  A_7: det = 8
  A_8: det = 9
  A_9: det = 10

  B_2: det = 2
  B_3: det = 2
  B_4: det = 2
  B_5: det = 2
  B_6: det = 2
  B_7: det = 2

  C_3: det = 2
  C_4: det = 2
  C_5: det = 2
  C_6: det = 2
  C_7: det = 2

  D_4: det = 4
  D_5: det = 4
  D_6: det = 4
  D_7: det = 4
  D_8: det = 4

Exceptional:
  G₂: det = 1
  F₄: det = 1
  E₆: det = 3
  E₇: det = 2
  E₈: det = 1

OBSERVATION: The Cartan determinant = |weight lattice / root lattice|
  = index of root lattice in weight lattice
  = order of the center of the simply-connected group

For A_n: det = n+1 = |Z(SU(n+1))| = |Z_{n+1}|
  A₁: Z₂ (2 = KEY₁)
  A₂: Z₃ (3 = KEY₂)

For the exceptionals:
  G₂: trivial center (det=1)
  F₄: trivial center (det=1)
  E₆: Z₃ center (det=3 = KEY₂!)
  E₇: Z₂ center (det=2 = KEY₁!)
  E₈: trivial center (det=1)

REMARKABLE: E₆ has center Z₃ and E₇ has center Z₂!
The two LARGEST non-trivial exceptionals carry our KEYS!
E₆ ↔ KEY₂ = 3, E₇ ↔ KEY₁ = 2

======================================================================
PART 2: PLATONIC SOLIDS AND THEIR SYMMETRY NUMBERS
======================================================================

Solid           V    E    F    |Rot|  χ=V-E+F  V·F    Schläfli
Tetrahedron     4    6    4    12     2        16     {3,3}
Cube            8    12   6    24     2        48     {4,3}
Octahedron      6    12   8    24     2        48     {3,4}
Dodecahedron    20   30   12   60     2        240    {5,3}
Icosahedron     12   30   20   60     2        240    {3,5}

ALL have Euler characteristic χ = V - E + F = 2 (genus 0)
This is the SPHERE relation — every Platonic solid is a 2-sphere.

KEY NUMBERS in Platonic solids:
  Rotation groups: |A₄|=12, |S₄|=24, |A₅|=60
  12 = 2²·3, 24 = 2³·3, 60 = 2²·3·5
  ALL are divisible by 6 = 2·3 = KEY₁·KEY₂!

  Vertex counts: 4, 6, 8, 12, 20
  4 = 2², 6 = 2·3, 8 = 2³, 12 = 2²·3, 20 = 2²·5
  8 and 6 are our KEY POWERS: 8 = KEY₁³, 6 = KEY₁·KEY₂

  Edge counts: 6, 12, 30
  6 = KEY₁·KEY₂, 12 = 2·KEY₁·KEY₂, 30 = 2·3·5

======================================================================
PART 3: THE ADE CLASSIFICATION
======================================================================

The ADE classification connects:
  1. Simply-laced Dynkin diagrams (A_n, D_n, E_6, E_7, E_8)
  2. Finite subgroups of SU(2)
  3. Simple singularities
  4. Regular polyhedra

The McKay correspondence:
  A_n ↔ Z_{n+1} (cyclic group)
  D_n ↔ Dic_{n-2} (binary dihedral, order 4(n-2))
  E_6 ↔ BT (binary tetrahedral, order 24)
  E_7 ↔ BO (binary octahedral, order 48)
  E_8 ↔ BI (binary icosahedral, order 120)

TOURNAMENT THEORY LIVES IN TYPE A:
  A_{n-1} ↔ Z_n ↔ S_n (Weyl group)
  Tournament on n vertices ↔ orientation of A_{n-1} root system

BUT: the Platonic solids enter via E₆, E₇, E₈!
  E₆ (tetrahedron): det = 3 = KEY₂
  E₇ (cube/octahedron): det = 2 = KEY₁
  E₈ (dodecahedron/icosahedron): det = 1

THE KEYS ARE ENCODED IN THE EXCEPTIONAL-PLATONIC CORRESPONDENCE:
  KEY₂ = 3 = det(E₆) ↔ tetrahedron (the SELF-DUAL solid)
  KEY₁ = 2 = det(E₇) ↔ cube/octahedron (the DUAL PAIR)
  1 = det(E₈) ↔ dodecahedron/icosahedron (the GOLDEN RATIO pair)

======================================================================
PART 4: TOURNAMENTS ON PLATONIC SOLID VERTICES
======================================================================

TETRAHEDRON (4 vertices):
  Total tournaments: 2^6 = 64
  Non-isomorphic: 4
  Symmetry group: A₄ (order 12) — alternating on 4 elements
  # orbits = 64/12 = 5.33... (not uniform orbits)

  H distribution: {1: 24, 3: 16, 5: 24}
  Possible H values: [1, 3, 5]
  Note: H ∈ {1, 3, 5} at n=4

OCTAHEDRON (6 vertices):
  Total tournaments: 2^15 = 32768
  Symmetry group: S₄ (order 24, acting on 3 pairs of antipodal vertices)

  Octahedron faces: 8 triangles
  T0: geo_3cyc=1/8, all_3cyc=5/C(6,3)=20, H=15
  T1: geo_3cyc=4/8, all_3cyc=6/C(6,3)=20, H=31
  T2: geo_3cyc=1/8, all_3cyc=1/C(6,3)=20, H=3
  T3: geo_3cyc=1/8, all_3cyc=4/C(6,3)=20, H=15
  T4: geo_3cyc=1/8, all_3cyc=3/C(6,3)=20, H=9

======================================================================
PART 5: THE COXETER NUMBER AND THE TOURNAMENT POLYNOMIAL
======================================================================

Coxeter numbers of simple Lie algebras:
  A_n: h = n+1
  B_n: h = 2n
  C_n: h = 2n
  D_n: h = 2(n-1)
  G₂: h = 6
  F₄: h = 12
  E₆: h = 12
  E₇: h = 18
  E₈: h = 30

COXETER NUMBERS OF THE EXCEPTIONALS:
  G₂: h=6 = 2·3 = KEY₁·KEY₂ = product of keys
  F₄: h=12 = 2²·3 = KEY₁²·KEY₂
  E₆: h=12 = 2²·3 = KEY₁²·KEY₂ (same as F₄!)
  E₇: h=18 = 2·3² = KEY₁·KEY₂² (9=KEY₂² appears!)
  E₈: h=30 = 2·3·5

THE 5 APPEARS ONLY IN E₈!
E₈ is the only exceptional group whose Coxeter number involves
a prime other than 2 and 3. The prime 5 enters through the
icosahedral symmetry (dodecahedron has C₅ symmetry).

TOURNAMENT POLYNOMIAL z² - 5z + 6 = 0:
  5 = Coxeter number of A₄ (rank 4)
  6 = Coxeter number of G₂ (rank 2)
  So the tournament polynomial has:
  coefficient 5 = h(A₄)
  coefficient 6 = h(G₂)
  roots 2 = det(A₁) = h(A₁)
  roots 3 = det(A₂) = h(A₂)


======================================================================
PART 6: THE 5-FOLD WAY
======================================================================

WHY FIVE? The number 5 appears as:

  5 Platonic solids
  5 exceptional Lie groups
  5 = 2 + 3 (sum of keys)
  5 = Φ₄(2) (fourth cyclotomic at 2)
  5 = h(A₄) (Coxeter number of A₄)
  5 = F(5) (Fibonacci fixed point)

THE DEEP REASON:
  5 = 2 + 3 is the diameter of the key pair.
  The 'classification gap' between keys 2 and 3.

  In ADE: A, D are INFINITE series. E₆, E₇, E₈ are FINITE exceptions.
  The E series ENDS at rank 8 (E₈). Why?
  Because E₉ would require a Coxeter number of 30+...
  Actually: the E-series stops because the Cartan matrix must
  be positive definite. E₈ is the last.

  In Platonic solids: they stop at 5 because higher-dimensional
  analogs would require dihedral angles impossible on a 2-sphere.
  The angle constraint is: π/(Schläfli number) must satisfy
  a positivity condition — same as Cartan matrix positive-definiteness!

  THE SAME POSITIVITY CONSTRAINT stops both sequences at 5!


======================================================================
PART 7: THE DUAL PAIRS AND THE KEYS
======================================================================

Platonic dual pairs:
  Tetrahedron ↔ Tetrahedron (self-dual)
  Cube ↔ Octahedron
  Dodecahedron ↔ Icosahedron

Tournament duality: T ↔ T̄ (reversal)
  H(T) = H(T̄) (proved in S75)
  The reversal is an INVOLUTION, like Platonic duality.

THE SELF-DUAL SOLID (tetrahedron) has:
  4 vertices, 6 edges, 4 faces
  Symmetry group |A₄| = 12 = 2²·3
  V = F = 4 = 2² = KEY₁²
  E = 6 = 2·3 = KEY₁·KEY₂

  In tournament theory, a 'self-dual' tournament is one with
  T ≅ T̄ (has an anti-automorphism).
  These are called SELF-COMPLEMENTARY tournaments.
  They exist only for n ≡ 3 (mod 4): n = 3, 7, 11, 15, ...

  At n=3: the 3-cycle C₃ is self-complementary (and is a
  tournament on the faces of a tetrahedron!)
  The tetrahedron has 4 vertices but its FACE graph is K₄,
  and orientations of K₃ (= face triples) give tournaments.


======================================================================
PART 8: THE ICOSAHEDRAL CONNECTION — WHERE 5 MEETS 2 AND 3
======================================================================

The icosahedron/dodecahedron pair is special:
  It introduces the GOLDEN RATIO φ = (1+√5)/2
  φ² = φ + 1 (the Fibonacci recurrence!)
  φ = 1.618... (the 2-nacci root!)

  The k-nacci roots:
  k=2: φ ≈ 1.618 (golden ratio, icosahedral)
  k=3: ≈ 1.839 (tribonacci, n=9 regime)
  k→∞: → 2 (KEY₁)

  The GOLDEN RATIO is the FIRST k-nacci root.
  It lives in Q(√5), the simplest quadratic extension.
  And √5 comes from the DISCRIMINANT of z²-5z+6:
  Δ = 25 - 24 = 1 → √Δ = 1 (trivial!)

  BUT: φ satisfies z² - z - 1 = 0, with Δ = 5.
  And 5 = the sum of keys = 2 + 3.
  So √5 = √(KEY₁ + KEY₂).

  The golden ratio φ = (1 + √(KEY₁+KEY₂)) / KEY₁

  ICOSAHEDRAL SYMMETRY meets tournament theory:
  The binary icosahedral group (BI) has order 120 = 5!
  It corresponds to E₈ in the McKay correspondence.
  E₈ is the LARGEST exceptional group.
  Its Coxeter number h(E₈) = 30 = 2·3·5.
  This is the PRODUCT of the three primes {2, 3, 5}.

  The HIERARCHY:
  Level 1: KEY₁ = 2 (binary, A₁, cycle orientations)
  Level 2: KEY₂ = 3 (ternary, A₂, cycle length)
  Level 3: 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂ (quintic, golden ratio, icosahedral)

  2, 3, 5 are the first three primes.
  They generate: 6=2·3, 10=2·5, 15=3·5, 30=2·3·5
  These are the Coxeter numbers of the ADE system!
  h(G₂)=6, h(A₉)=10, h(A₁₄)=15, h(E₈)=30


======================================================================
PART 9: THE TOURNAMENT ON THE ICOSAHEDRON
======================================================================

The icosahedron has 12 vertices, 30 edges, 20 triangular faces.
A tournament on 12 vertices has C(12,2) = 66 edges.
The icosahedron graph has 30 edges — less than half of 66.

But the FACE graph of the icosahedron has 20 faces,
each a triple of vertices. In a tournament, each triple
is either a 3-cycle (prob 3/4) or transitive (prob 1/4).

Expected # of 3-cycle faces: 20 · 3/4 = 15
Expected α₁ at n=12: C(12,3)/4 = 55
Face 3-cycles / total 3-cycles ≈ 15/55 ≈ 27%

The 20 icosahedral faces decompose into:
  10 pairs of opposite faces (antipodal)
  5 'rings' of 4 faces each (around each edge pair)

If we orient the tournament to MAXIMIZE 3-cycles among faces:
  Want all 20 face triples to be 3-cycles
  This constrains 20 · 3 = 60 edge orientations (with overlaps)
  The icosahedron has 30 edges, each shared by 2 faces
  So 40 constraints on 30 edges — OVERDETERMINED
  Can we achieve all 20? Probably not.


======================================================================
PART 10: E₈ AND THE TOURNAMENT AT n=8
======================================================================

E₈ has rank 8, dim 248.
A tournament on 8 vertices lives in type A₇ (rank 7).

BUT: E₈ has deep connections to tournaments:
  dim(E₈) = 248 = 8·31 = 8·(2⁵-1) = 8·Mersenne(5)
  The number of positive roots: 120 = 5!
  The Coxeter number: 30 = 2·3·5
  The exponents: 1, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19, 23, 29 (primes < 30!)

  E₈ exponents are EXACTLY the integers coprime to 30 in [1,29]:
  These are the totatives of 30 = 2·3·5.
  φ(30) = 30·(1-1/2)·(1-1/3)·(1-1/5) = 8
  So E₈ has rank = φ(h) = φ(30) = 8!

  THIS IS THE KEY RELATIONSHIP:
  rank(E₈) = φ(h(E₈)) = φ(2·3·5) = 8
  The rank of E₈ is the EULER TOTIENT of its Coxeter number!

  For type A_{n-1}: rank = n-1, h = n
  φ(h) = φ(n) — not equal to rank in general
  But: φ(p) = p-1 = rank for prime n=p!
  So A_{p-1} has rank = φ(h) when h=p is prime.

  h(A₁) = 2 (prime): rank = 1 = φ(2) ✓
  h(A₂) = 3 (prime): rank = 2 = φ(3) ✓
  h(A₄) = 5 (prime): rank = 4 = φ(5) ✓
  h(A₆) = 7 (prime): rank = 6 = φ(7) ✓

  The KEY primes 2, 3, 5, 7 all give rank = φ(h)!
  These are the primes dividing 30 = h(E₈)... plus 7.

======================================================================
PART 11: THE RECURRENCE VIEW — (2,3,5) HIERARCHY
======================================================================

  LEVEL 1 (KEY₁ = 2):
  z² - z - 1 = 0 → φ = (1+√5)/2 ≈ 1.618 (Fibonacci)
  z - 2 = 0 → x = 2 (evaluation point for H)
  Binary choice: each cycle has 2 orientations

  LEVEL 2 (KEY₂ = 3):
  z² - 5z + 6 = 0 → roots 2, 3 (tournament polynomial)
  Ternary structure: each cycle uses 3 vertices
  n=9 = 3² is the CS boundary

  LEVEL 3 (5 = KEY₁ + KEY₂):
  z² - 5z + 5 = 0 → roots (5±√5)/2 ≈ 3.618, 1.382
  These are φ² = φ+1 and 1/φ² = ... no.
  Actually: the roots are φ³ = 2+φ ≈ 3.618 and φ⁻³ ≈ ... no.

  Better: 5 appears as the DISCRIMINANT of the Fibonacci polynomial.
  Δ(z²-z-1) = 1+4 = 5
  And Δ(z²-5z+6) = 25-24 = 1 (trivial!)

  The tournament polynomial has DISCRIMINANT 1 (perfect square).
  The Fibonacci polynomial has DISCRIMINANT 5 (= sum of keys).

  TOGETHER:
  Fibonacci (k=2): gives φ → approaches KEY₁=2 as k→∞
  Tournament poly: gives KEY₁=2, KEY₂=3 directly
  The bridge: 5 = discriminant of Fibonacci = sum of keys

  THE THREE POLYNOMIALS:
  z - 2 = 0            (KEY₁)
  z² - z - 1 = 0       (Fibonacci, disc = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂)
  z² - 5z + 6 = 0      (tournament, disc = 1, roots = keys)

  They form a HIERARCHY:
  1st poly degree 1: gives 2
  2nd poly degree 2: gives φ (approaches 2)
  3rd poly degree 2: gives 2 and 3

======================================================================
PART 12: SYNTHESIS — THE FIVE-FOLD TOURNAMENT UNIVERSE
======================================================================

  THE FIVE EXCEPTIONAL GROUPS ↔ FIVE TOURNAMENT STRUCTURES:

  G₂ (det=1, h=6=2·3):
    The MINIMAL exceptional. 'Octonion structure.'
    Tournament analog: the 6-vertex tournament (first α₂>0)
    h = 6 = product of keys = first non-trivial independence level

  F₄ (det=1, h=12):
    'Exceptional Jordan algebra.' 52-dimensional.
    Tournament analog: n=12 (first α₄>0)
    h = 12 = 4·3 = threshold for 4 disjoint 3-cycles

  E₆ (det=3, h=12):
    Center = Z₃ = KEY₂!
    McKay: binary tetrahedral (order 24)
    Tournament analog: the KEY₂ structure
    Tetrahedron = self-dual solid = self-complementary tournament

  E₇ (det=2, h=18):
    Center = Z₂ = KEY₁!
    McKay: binary octahedral (order 48)
    Tournament analog: the KEY₁ structure (binary orientation)
    h = 18 = 2·9 = 2·KEY₂² (the CS boundary!)

  E₈ (det=1, h=30):
    Center = trivial. The LARGEST exceptional.
    McKay: binary icosahedral (order 120 = 5!)
    Tournament analog: the COMPLETE structure
    h = 30 = 2·3·5 = product of first 3 primes
    rank = 8 = φ(30) = 2³ = KEY₁³

  THE MASTER TABLE:
  Group  det   h     McKay order    Key      Tournament n
  G₂     1     6     12             2·3      n=6
  F₄     1     12    24             2²·3     n=12
  E₆     3     12    24             KEY₂     n=12 (self-dual)
  E₇     2     18    48             KEY₁     n=18=2·9=2·3²
  E₈     1     30    120            2·3·5    n=30
